The template class is far better than the old, and simple %replace_with_something% theming system. 

The general format of any template tag is:

		<%templ func(arg1, arg2, ...); func2(arg1, arg2, ...) %>

		/* constructor */
		function template()

		Tag Related functions
		----------------------------

		A tag is a simple replacement operation. Tags can be a variable, define, include, anything.
		

		function addTag($tagName, $type)
			Lower level add function, I suggest using the other add functions instead of this one
			Adds a tag named $tagName with type $type. Stores all other arguments passed to it in an
			array. If a tag exists, it returns FALSE, otherwise TRUE

		function tagExists($tagName)
			returns TRUE if a tag exists, otherwise FALSE

		function deleteTag($tagName)
			removes a tag. Returns TRUE if tag is removed, FALSE if tag doesn't exist.


		******************************************************************************************
		NOTE: All of these functions return FALSE if the tag already exists, TRUE otherwise.
		Some of the functions will return FALSE based on other criteria, that will be mentioned
		below.
		******************************************************************************************

		function addTagInclude($tagName, $include)
			Add a tag $tagName, the contents of $tagName are replaced with file $include
			Returns FALSE if the file doesn't exist

		function addTagFunction($tagName, $function)
			Add a tag $tagName, the output of $function are caught using output buffering. The
			return value of the function is dicarded. No arguments are passed to this function.

			The function is not checked to exist, as it can be declared after the addTag() call

		function addTagReturnFunction($tagName, $function)
			Add a tag $tagName, the contents of $function are replaced with the
			return value. No arguments are passed to this function.

			The function is not checked to exist, as it can be declared after the addTag() call

		function addTagDefine($tagName, $define)
			Adds a tag $tagname, returning the value of the define $define. A define is created
			with the PHP define() function.

		function addTagVariable($tagName, $variable)
			Adds a tag $tagName, it's value is replaced with $variable, out of the $GLOBALS array

		function addTagPostVariable($tagName, $variable)
			Adds a tag $tagName, it's value is replaced with $variable, out of the $_POST array

		function addTagGetVariable($tagName, $variable) {
			Adds a tag $tagName, it's value is replaced with $variable, out of the $_GET array

		function loadTemplate($resource, $template_data)
			This function is a helper, I don't recommend calling it directly, See below.

			For the hardcore: $resource is just a name describing the $template_data, like where it came
			from. $template_data is a string. $resource is not used yet but might be in the future.

		function loadTemplateFromFile($file)
			Resource name: 'file'
			Loads a template from $file, returns TRUE if the file exists and was loaded ok. FALSE if not.

		function loadTemplateFromString($string)
			Resource name: 'string'
			Loads a template from a string, returns TRUE


		The following doTag* functions don't need to be called directly, they're used internally,
		and are pretty self explanatory.

		function doTagDefine($define)
		function doTagInclude($include)
		function doTagFunction($function)
		function doTagReturnFunction($function)
		function doTagVariable($variable)
		function doTagPostVariable($variable)
		function doTagGetVariable($variable)


		function loadModule($file)
			Loads a module, See the modules section


		More internal functions... Parser & code related

		function parserHasWork($data)

		function codeParser($code, $len)
		function doCodeParser($code, $len)

		function doParseTemplate($data)
		function parseTemplate()

		function doTemplateCode($code_block, $code_len)

		These functions do the Tag code, Echo code and date code respectively

		function doTemplateTag($tag)
		function doTemplateEcho($str)
		function doTemplateDate($format)


Supported template functions:
----------------------------

	These functions are invoked like:

	<%templ echo(Hello World); %>


	echo(string)
		Echos out a string
	
	date(format)
		Prints the date

	
	tag(tagName)
		Prints the output of tag
